Set 1

Hell In A Bucket 
Bertha 
Walkin' Blues 
Ramble On Rose 
Beat It On Down The Line 
Big Railroad Blues 
Just Like Tom Thumb's Blues 
Let It Grow 

Set 2

Sugar Magnolia ->
Foolish Heart ->
Playing In The Band ->
Terrapin Station ->
Drums ->
Space ->
The Wheel ->
Black Peter ->
Around And Around ->
Sunshine Daydream 

Encore
Box Of Rain

reviews.review_text:
ear candy Man, this is serious ear candy.  It helps that they do all my favorite songs in that first set too. I was always encouraged by a Hell in a Bucket opener because it had developed into a song that could get out there very quickly by that jam.  It was their most 80’s song in many ways, the palette of sounds is not unlike R.E.M. in its use of layering  a wash of guitars with notes that only occasionally pop to the surface.  Like a fool, I was relieved by 91 when a Bucket didn’t turn directly into a Sugaree.  I guess I was spoiled by too many 85-89 shows.  

But back to the ear candy.  I’m talking about the recording which just settles on the ears like a good doobie.  I have no quarrel with the talkative New Yawk crowd; it’s FOB and the band is present, under your chin; you can hear the sound hitting the floorboards.  

I never really liked this MSG run until hearing these Brennecke recordings.  Due to the taper section-a mixed blessing after 1986-it was harder for tapers to get a full sound and the soundboards from this year in particular seem too crowded but that’s really because the stage was.  The Dead take their time here, which is exemplified in the slow, loping Let it Grow that closes a set which takes a meandering walk through their older catalogue at a relaxed and gentle pace. 

When they start tuning up with “I Want to Tell You”, I was wracking my brain because I did not recollect them busting that hot mess out this early.  I wonder if the apparent lack of recognition from the crowd put the kibosh on it because it really seems like they’re about to break it out.  Sugar Magnolia is better though, but it’s post 88 so is it going to suddenly truncate and turn into Victim or something???…and lurch! Yep, it does.  Jerry doesn’t even let Bob finish poor old Sugar Magnolia off before he’s wagging his unenthusiastic finger at the couple in Foolish Heart.  Sugar Magnolia is truly a sunshine daydream that ends much too soon.  What happened to the un-rushed atmosphere and perambulations of the first set?  Where did it go?  Up the nose probably…Shadoobee.  

At this point I’m hoping for Playin’ and kind of expecting it dammit since they only did that little untethered snippet the opening night.  And yes they do it but if you blinked, you missed it.  Is it shorter than that one at Worcester Centrum a couple of years back. Maybe not but it's not as memorable either.  The rest of the set is nice; there's a repeat which must have been unwelcome but that's a very nice Box of Rain in the encore. Don't leave for the parking lot too early.
